node.text: Got to catch up with my favorite human @shannonrwatts for a quick tutorial on how to phone bank (a critical step in this phase of the election cycle when we aren’t knocking on doors). You can do this while you watch TV with a glass of wine. And anyone can do it. It’s fun and so easy! we also discuss what you should be watching on tv, important election reminders, and how sleep deprived and delirious we are. Please watch and share! Let’s phone bank!!! 💪☎️ #teamjoetalks @joebiden @votejoe

node.text:
Drea, my dear friend and mentor. I don’t think I have ever known anyone like you. You were the axis around which we all rotated. Your light was the brightest I have ever experienced. The smartest, coolest, wittiest, and MOST fun. Who else travels for work with tequila and a poker set? The greatest mom. The friend that always rallied and showed up. The arbiter of British crime shows and vintage. Bold, daring, and always so clear on the path forward. And my God, the best taste of anyone I have ever known. All of us just wanted to be around you. To be like you. It is the greatest privilege to have known and loved you. To see you every day. I cannot imagine a world without your giant heart and your bright light. But promise, to never forget all you have shared with and taught us. 
Steve, Ryan, Booke, and Jade, sending you our prayers and hoping you feel the sea of love that surrounds you. 

(Couldn’t resist that last photo. I will never forget your giggle and joy the moment you texted us this photo) Love you, Dre @andreabstanford ❤️❤️🕊❤️❤️

Nearly 40 years ago, Army vet Willie Simmons was sentenced to life in prison for a robbery he committed in Alabama. He was prosecuted under the state's Habitual Felony Offenders Act, a law that was passed in the 1970s to crack down on repeat offenders. Simmons had three felonies on his record, but none of them were violent.

I #WearOrange today on National Gun Violence Awareness Day to shine a light on the gun violence crisis that takes more than 100 lives and wounds hundreds more every day. We can end gun violence together. 

Orange is the color Hadiya Pendleton’s friends wore in her honor after she was fatally shot in Chicago at age 15 in 2013. After her death, her friends wore orange - the color hunters wear in the woods to protect themselves - to raise awareness about gun violence.

Text ORANGE to 64433 to ​join a virtual event  @shannonrwatts @momsdemand @everytown
